b) (2 marks)

The first principal component is made up of a relatively equal weight of all the variables. However, MPG ratings, RPM, and Rev.per.mile are all negatively associated with the first component. We can somewhat view this component as a measure of the `size’ of the car, since large cars will have high scores on all the positively correlated variables and smaller scores on the four negatively associated variables.

c) (2 marks)

The second principal component is a bit less clear. We have a high positive loading of price, horsepower, and RPM, along with large negative loadings for MPG and rear seats, luggage. This suggests relatively small, expensive cars with strong engines. It seems we could potentially interpret this as a measure of “luxuriousness”.

f) (2 marks)

The fact that LDA can find the structure of Small vs Not-Small cars in the first fit suggests to some extent that our interpretation of the first component (size of car) may well hold true. In terms of LDA using all car types, we can see Compact, Small, Midsize, and Large all being largely distinguishable through the first two components. The only category of car that is poorly classified is Sporty.

We should consider one of the standardized distance measures, as even though the measuring units are the same across each bill measurement, the scale is quite different across them (Diagonal has a standard deviation > 4 times Left, for instance).

(Mahalanobis is probably a poor choice here as it scales across the covariance of all the observations, not group-wise, in this context, but I wouldn’t take marks off if this is the route that a student goes)

(b) [3 marks]

bank_scaled_dist <- dist(scale(banknote[,-c(1,2)]))
plot(hclust(bank_scaled_dist, method="single"))

plot(hclust(bank_scaled_dist, method="complete"))

plot(hclust(bank_scaled_dist, method="average"))

(c) [2 marks]

The complete linkage dendrogram appears to give the clearest group structure. Both single linkage and average linkage will put several observations in their own group.

(d) [2 marks]

The dendogram suggests a choice of K=2 or K=3, I will go forward with K=2

hcres <- cutree(hclust(bank_scaled_dist, method="complete"), 2)
table(banknote$Status, hcres)
##              hcres
##                 1   2
##   counterfeit 100   0
##   genuine      30  70
30/200 #misclassification rate
## [1] 0.15

We misclassify 30 genuine notes into the group that is made of primarily counterfeit notes, for a misclassification rate of 0.15.

(e) [2 marks]

set.seed(632)
kscale <- kmeans(scale(banknote[,-c(1,2)]), 2)
table(banknote$Status, kscale$clus)
##              
##                 1   2
##   counterfeit 100   0
##   genuine       8  92
8/200 #misclassification rate
## [1] 0.04

For this run of kmeans, we misclassify 8 genuine notes into the group that is made of primarily counterfeit notes, for a misclassification rate of 0.04.

(f) [2 marks]

set.seed(632)
kraw <- kmeans(banknote[,-c(1,2)], 2)
table(banknote$Status, kraw$clus)
##              
##                 1   2
##   counterfeit   0 100
##   genuine     100   0
0/200 #misclassification rate
## [1] 0

For this run of kmeans on the raw data, we misclassify none of the bank notes for a rate of 0! This actually goes against our generalized rules discussed in class. Since we are looking at the raw data, predictors with high variability will dominate while building groups. It happens, in this case, that one of the higher variability predictors (Diagonal) actually provides a clearer picture of the two groups than the lower variability predictors (such as Left). Hence, this is a case where standardization will actually hurt us in finding the known group structure within the data.

(g) [2 marks]

Overall, the strong performance of the clustering algorithms tells us that there is a very strong group structure in the data — which actually corresponds to the known categories of counterfeit and genuine bills.

(f) [3 marks]

Each run provides a different result with respect to classification of the true groups, which is surprising as the groups structures are relatively clear (as seen in part ‘a’). We could also tell this from viewing the within group sum of squares for each:

r1$tot.withinss
## [1] 14366.82
r2$tot.withinss
## [1] 6892.684
r3$tot.withinss
## [1] 4037.198
r4$tot.withinss
## [1] 4365.592

It’s worth noting that the runs with many random starts (r3 and r4) have significantly lower within group sum of squares than the individual runs (r1 and r2). r4 has a slightly higher ARI value than r3, so even with 1000 random starts, we are not achieving stability in the results. All of this illustrates concerns with k-means being able to consistently find the global minima for data with this many groups.
